segments.text: missed you completely would you please stop it testing one two three stop it please we don't have much the first question is um what were some of the highlights of your years in the house of representatives well it depends on whose opinion in your opinion it takes uh
I guess being leader of the time that Termin was Speaker of the House, and one of the, I guess, aggressive things that I was chairman of the committee that made
University of Houston was a fully state-supported school.
Before this bill was passed, it was supported as a junior college, but not as a senior college.
And I was chairman of the committee that recommended
and passed in the House that it be made a full state-supported school.
Because at that time, Houston was paying 1 20th of the state taxes.
And my committee thought that they should have a full state-supported school.
if they're paying that much taxes.
And the people were there to support it.
When I went through the House journals in your first session that you were in, there weren't that many ag bills passed.
Why was this?
What was most important during that session?
Well, there wasn't many ag bills paid because at that particular time, there weren't many introduced.
And the tax
bill was the main thing that took up most of the time.
What kind of power, in your opinion, did Price Daniel have over the House?
That was like his last year as governor.
Price Daniel, senior.
Yes.
Oh, I thought he did well.
I think Price Daniel, senior, was one of our better governors.
I happened to be on his team.
Maybe that's why I think so.
He gave me most everything I asked for.
In fact, my daughter worked for him, too.
Peggy worked for him.
Oh, really?
During the summer.
I noticed that.
She was secretary at two of his people that were newspaper people.
And she made out the certificates at the Admiral of the Navy and et cetera.
Can I tell you a little joke on it?
Mm-hmm.
Well, John wasn't too old at that time either, you know.
And so she got a blank, and she filled it out, making it.
John David, king of the apes of the Congo.
And she mailed it officially, put Price Daniels, she signed, had authority to sign Price Daniels' name.
She signed Price Daniels' name to it and sent it to him.
Oh, it made him so mad.
It made him so mad.
I read that he was mascot your first session also, John David.
Your first session I also read in the journal that LBJ spoke in front of the House a lot.
What kind of influence did he have over the Texas House, and how did the Texas House help him in his running for presidency?
Before that time, you could not hold a public office and run for another one.
Well, we passed a bill with the Senate that you could.
That made him then eligible to run for the president.
That bill was passed in no time.
He wanted it.
He got it.
Was that like for almost anything he wanted?
I wouldn't say that, but he never did ask for it.
Oh, he didn't ask for this?
Yeah, he had to have this to run for president.
He was running for president.
Then, of course, Jack Kennedy was nominated president, and then Kennedy asked him to be his vice president.
And this gave him authority to do that, this bill did.
I read that you were the...

campaign chairman for rural texans for johnson and humphrey um what area of texas is involved this is the whole state the whole state so um what kind of things did you do well i got uh people from every county that uh put had one man from every county to uh get out and support uh
like the county judge or the most of what I would think would be the most influential people.
And then I traveled a lot.
And I guess the greatest thing of that time, the best thing that I did was asking Dan Blocker, who we called Hawks Cartwright, to come down on a weekend and travel
and make speeches.
I had a man in Fort Worth that would furnish a plane, and he would come down on Friday or Saturday morning early.
We'd throw him out of Hollywood down here.
Maybe that weekend I was going to start out
for work.
We're at that time forward.
Fair was going on.
And so we flew in there and started out there and making he made speeches.
Johnson.
And we do that.
We're not we.
He drew the crowds.
People just
Those thousands would come just to hear him and see him in person.
Was he from Texas?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Yeah.
Wow.
How did you get that chairmanship?
Did Johnson ask you?
Johnson and some of his people knew that I knew lots of people over the state.
When I worked on it, I would work hard.
I wouldn't, you know.
That's kind of braggadocious.
And he was a very good speaker.
Very good speaker.
Blocker?
Uh-huh.
And I never will forget, we had...
meeting in the temple.
And we filled that whole square up with prayer in the temple.
And when we landed, a little girl out at the airport, a little girl came up and gave him some flowers.
And she just reached over and did this.
And she ran back to her mother saying, Mama, I touched him.
I touched him.
I touched him.
So apparently did he do in Corpus Christi was very, very large.
And the valley was very large.
By having an airplane.
We didn't we didn't tear it along in these places.
One all day affair by any means, we tried to make at least five.
And we did this.
I believe five weekends previous to the election.
Hmm.
Um, so rural Texans or Texans really liked LBJ.
What did they think of him?
What did, in your opinion?
Well, he carried counties that, uh, that had gone Republican previous all the time.
And he carried, he carried the counties.
I don't remember the votes.
It's,
That's a long go.
But actually, you know, you'd want your native son to be president or vice president.
I would set up these meetings.
whether the county judges or the district judge, or the district attorney in the county and the surrounding counties.
You know, bring people see people got there.
We had had it on radio and TV, etc.
In our history class, we learned that what LBJ called his great society programs, a lot of domestic programs, how did it affect Texas and rural America and the cities?
Well, the greatest thing that he did for the rural people is the REA.
And what is that?
Rural electricity.
What we call like a blue body co-op.
Oh, like a co-op?
Yeah, but the REA was the mother of the whole thing.
They furnished, they formed the co-ops.
And he tried to get the private utilities to run electricity to the farmers, but he didn't.
So he got some money, federal money.
And then they formed these co-ops, like Blue Bonnie, .
And Pertinallis was the largest, Bluebonnet's largest now.
I didn't know that.
And I guess Pertinallis, I did have a list of them here, but I mean, somewhat.
Pertinallis is second, and then they go on down.
In the 58th, well, the second session that you were in the House of Representatives,

I noticed that there were a lot of bills passed through the House for improvement of colleges and universities and school districts, like pertaining to special services and teacher salaries and textbooks.
That's right.
What kind of impact did it have on, like, Lee, Bastrop, and Burleson counties?
Well, it just brought in more money for the counties, like the teachers' pay raise.
The speaker was a
James A. Turman had his doctorate, graduated to Commerce.
And he was full, wholehearted for the teachers.
Consequently, he did all he could for the teachers and for schools.
And that's the reason that there's more done in that session at that particular time for schools
and school teachers.
However, he did not get as much as he wanted, because at that particular time, the House and Senate both were very conservative.
Did this area have new school buildings built or anything like that, just mostly salaries?
Mostly salaries, I'd say.
I don't remember whether there were any new school buildings at that particular time built or not.
I just don't remember.
As the deputy commissioner in the Ag Department and as a legislator, how did Texas react to the civil rights as far as in the House and in the Agriculture Department?
Because this was the time of big civil rights.
Well, I think it, I believe it went along fairly well because they started hiring blacks and Mexican Americans.
In fact, I did the hiring in the agriculture department.
and i hired quite a few blacks and uh and mexican americans and uh of course nationally i would get to get to higher educated people that hold higher higher jobs for instance uh ernesto de leon from
from Brownsville.
He was a graduate from A&M.
He was out in West Texas.
And I went out there and talked to him into coming with us.
And he just quit.
Just quit.
He traveled a lot into Mexico and Central America, selling cattle to Texas.
As far as civil rights, was the House conservative or liberal about passing it?
It was still conservative.
I knew they had to pass it, but it was still conservative.
Then when I started the first...
equal rights committee in the state departments.
I selected two whites, two Anglos, I mean two blacks, and two Mexican-Americans.
And if any of the people that we had hired out in the fields had a quarrel with their boss or they had trouble of various kinds, they would take this to this committee.
And the committee would vote which was right, which was wrong.
And we did not, I didn't fire anybody if this committee said it was right.
Were these men?
It was women, too.
Oh, women, too?
Well, I'll tell you who.
This lady.
She's working there.
She left now, Black Lady Lois Jones.
I had her on the committee.
And I didn't put the hierarchy on this committee.
I put various people of degrees of labor.
You know, people that did the common labor and some of the...
I believe it was two people out of, two or three, two, I guess, out of the main office.
The rest of them were scattered around the state on this committee, and they would meet every month to discuss what they thought was right, how they thought things were going, and equal rights.
After I did that, some of the rest of the departments followed.
Did you hire a lot of women, or was this an area that women just didn't get into yet?
No, we hired quite a few women.
Like down in the valley, we even put women
to testing scales, testing gasoline pumps.
Actually, we were kind of leaders in promoting women in these jobs.
Well, besides that, can you tell me some other things that you felt

were important some of the accomplishments and aims and shortcomings that you had as deputy commissioner because you were in there for a very long time well uh i i guess one of the biggest things was the tap program which uh i thought of that between here and austin
See, I was going back and forth.
And when you're out riding BCF, you can concentrate.
Anyway, I thought about that, this TAF program, which is agricultural products.
And then I had every car that was controlled by the Department of Agriculture.
A sign on it.
You've seen them, I know.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
Some of my friends lobbied, teased me, said this is talk about Perrette.
That's a good one.
Well... Then we asked...
people like the egg industry, for instance, to put that on their cartons so that people would know that that was a Texas egg rather than a Louisiana or Arkansas.
And it helped the Texas poultry industry considerably.
How long did it take you to

instigate this project a year and a half to talk to all the different we went around and talked to i say we the the division people around and then we put up uh point of purchase signs in the stores saying this is a texas product
And we had even had a foul suit against some Arkansas people.
They had, they got a hold of it somewhere or another.
Tapsig printed on their cartons and was sending them into Texas.
And we had, we had the law to trace it down, find it.
And we brought a suit.
Of course, they quit.
Were these products just sold in Texas, or they went out of the country or just out of the state?
Oh, yeah, they went out of the state.
Did they go out of the country?
Yeah, we sold some stuff to Japan, and we sold some stuff to Mexico.
And I love Canada.
How did the farmers feel about selling it to people outside our country?
Oh, yeah, they liked it.
They liked it because they were getting the money?
Sure, sure, sure.
Mexico bought lots of our cattle.
Then we put stations, cattle stations,
I thought of this between here and Austin, too.
And I asked them.
Luckily, I had good friends in the house that would help me to get the money.
And we put cattle stations in Brownsville, Laredo, Del Rio, Eagle Pass, El Paso.
And these cattle had to be inspected by Mexico's vet and our vet.
And they would be put in these pens, and that's where the inspection would take place.
So who were the legislators that helped you
in the House to get things passed?
When I was deputy commissioner, Bill Heatley, Paducah, Sam Collins-Newton, Bill Hallowell of Grand Chalangin, scattered all over.
Were these men mostly from rural areas that your programs would help?
But you'd be surprised at that particular time.
The city boys would help you because a lot of them didn't know anything about it.
And they said, well, Bill, if you know what you know and you say it's right, I'll go along with you.
I'll vote with you.
I just luckily had to trust it enough to do it.
As Deputy Commissioner, what kind of impact did LBJ have on the Agriculture Department of Texas?
Did he help you all out in any way?
We asked for something in particular, but we never did ask him for much of anything.
He asked us.
Oh, really?
Yeah, he asked us to get some...
pecan trees out of Mexico, and some grapefruit trees out of Mexico.
How did the Vietnam War affect the agriculture department?
Not really?
No.
I noticed, I tried to find some information like in the local papers and things like that,
And I could hardly find anything about what was happening in Texas.
It was like they just wrote about Vietnam.
How did you promote, what other ways did you promote some of the ag programs and get the information to the people?
Because it didn't seem like they had that much in the papers.
I'll tell you what.
We had...
We were what we call tap luncheons.
And we had one in New York.
We had one in all over the state and the larger towns.
And it would be nothing served but Texas products.
And we would invite out-of-town, out-of-state people to these luncheons.
Have you ever heard of Ms. Corbett?
Well, now, she helped me.
She really helped me.
In fact, she was in New York.
We were putting this on in New York.
And I wasn't there.
I was in the Valley.
And she finally got a hold of me.
And Ben Bayesden was chief of marketing who did Seahawks.
And we shipped so many steaks to New York.
I've forgotten how many it was.
Anyway, she
finally got a hold of me in, I believe it was in Michigan, and she said, Bill, these states are not worth what we're trying to do.
Well, I said, I'll tell you what you do.
You call the packing
I said, we've been buying these sticks from here in Texas.
And tell them to airmail you the kind of the sticks that you want.
And that I, certain man there, I said, tell them that I told you to do it so you'd be sure that they'd get their money.
And she did.
She gave these other sticks away.
And Miss Cook up here at Austin, she put on, she helped us too.
Because it promoted their name.
And I guess the largest one we had was in Dallas.
Unless it had been New York.
I wasn't that one in New York.
Where...
I believe it was during the State Fair, where these out-of-town people, buyers, would be invited to come to taste these Texas products.
And we sold lots of them.
And the people that sold them were Texas people.
And of course, they were there, too.
And then we had another thing there at the State Fair in Dallas where we promoted the TAP program.
They had one big building up there.
Now, don't take this at heart, but A&M had it.
They called us.
They talked to Ben Bayesden, and Ben said he'd like to talk to me.
So we met them up there at this building.
What A&M was doing, they were in this building showing Grandma's canned peas and Grandma's canned...
fruits and vegetables and fodder and corn and stuff like that.
Well, it wasn't drawing people into the building.
And naturally, they wanted people to come to the fair.
So they turned the building over to us five.
And then we went out and got...
Blue Bell, all over the valley, people that manufactured and canned fruits and vegetables in East Texas.
Then we'd have a school choir would come in one weekend or maybe on a certain day
or maybe another band state where these things were manufactured.
And that drew a lot of people into the building.
And we had a room set off where out of state people would come.
and where we could talk to them and get the sellers and buyers together.
Where a lot of produce was, like turkeys and things, all kinds.
Is there a tap building at the fair?
Yeah.
Now?
Yeah.
Do you feel like this program is still successful?
It can be made successful as hard as the people want to make it.
In fact, John White, a gentleman from Dallas, before all this Iran stuff started, they went to the embassy in Iran, in Washington.
had just about completed trading produce, Texas agricultural products, for oil.
And then all that stuff blew up over there.
But first, the federal government came along and told us that we could not do that.
A state, a lone state, cannot trade or barter with a foreign country.
It has to go through the federal government.
Well, then you come along with the wheat people would be against it because they wouldn't have enough wheat.
We didn't raise these other states' rates and stuff like that.
So consequently, they knocked it in the head to start with.
But we would have sold lots and lots of Texas products if that could have gone through.
Did y'all do that with any other countries or go through the federal?
Couldn't.
The federal government wouldn't let us.
Did you ever go through the federal government to sell to other countries?
In Mexico, we did cattle, yeah.
And, uh, we went to, uh, we would ship cattle to, uh, Burma and to, uh, Australia, to, uh, uh, some of the Far East, uh, countries.
They would, uh, we shipped those.
We flew them out of, uh, Houston, all over.
Even cattle that these people bought in Amarillo would be brought to Houston.
I've seen goats, sheep, hogs, cattle, horses, astroturf, all kinds of seed put in one plane.
Brammer cattle.
Oh my goodness.
You were mentioning A&M, and since I'm from A&M, how did the universities have an impact on the agricultural department?
I noticed that like for the TAP program, what I read about it was as far as seeds and other kind of things, A&M had a part in it, University of Texas, Texas Tech.
Did they help you all a lot at all?
To be honest and straight with you, he and him were jealous of us.
Why?
Because we thought of this program.
And because we were making hay with it.
And I don't know whether Black's still over there or not.
Professor Black?
I don't know.
And I know he made the remark around the state that that wasn't nice and all.
In fact, one of them asked me, he said, oh, y'all will give that up soon, won't you?
What they want to do, they want us to give it up so they can get it.
But I never did call on them for anything.
Like Tarleton was great on peaches.
That's part of painting, yeah?
And some of those...
schools, Texas Tech, they would help us with things that we might need, help us find things.
And A&M did too, but A&M, they were kind of the hierarchy, not the... With the diversity of the state, what
Where did y'all center on most of the time?
Like Central Texas, East Texas, West Texas?
I mean, all over?
We had people all over the state.
But y'all didn't really center on any area?
No.
Like cattle, mostly East Texas and South Texas.
Wasn't too many from West Texas.
There's a few.
There's a lot of sheep and goats out of West Texas.
that went through the Del Rio pens.
What other projects did you help instigate when you were deputy commissioner?
Any other biggies?
I might think so, Matthew Lee.
Those two were the, no question about it, the two of them, it took lots of time, lots of,
That's where we spent most of our money, because it was helping the farmer.
Well, seed.
In our seed program, we tested seed in Mexico.
You'd go out here, you had maize.
Well, just as soon as your maize was harvested and cured, tested, we'd go to Mexico with it and plant it.
That way, we could tell this grower
what the percent of his, it was county, you know, and we had a fellow still doing it too, a fellow named Williams.
He's Mexican, but he's, I ain't gonna look at him.
He got Mexican, you know, he owns part of the land down there.
He lives down there.
We could give him the percentage.
you can get the tag and say percentage of the way it looked, foreign seed that was in it.
And our people would go down there and stay and plant it and watch it.
They'd come home for a week or two and go back for it.
We had a seed lab in Houston, which wasn't anything, not anything.
So I talked to a team, gave me the money, put up this seed lab.
Of course, the seed people, they wanted up McGregor because that is just about the center
of the seed growing in a lot of south, a lot of west, a lot of not much east, but up in Vernon and places like that.
Well, since I had the money, I could say where I wanted it.
Consequently, I said, well, I'm going to put it in my hometown, and I gave some reasons.

I said, well, at that time, I said we had trains coming through, and we had four truck lines crisscrossing here, you know, and we could get better service than off, like McGregor, off on one main highway.
And we had...
the labor that we can get to do it.
